The '''Guantanamo Bay detention camp''',<ref group="note">{{langx|es|Centro de detención de la bahía de Guantánamo}}</ref> also known as '''GTMO''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|ɪ|t|m|oʊ}} {{Respell|GIT|moh}}), '''GITMO''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|ɪ|t|m|oʊ}} {{Respell|GIT|moh}}), or simply '''Guantanamo Bay''', is a [[United States]] [[military prison]] within [[Naval Station Guantanamo Bay]] (NSGB), on the coast of [[Guantánamo Bay]], Cuba. It was established in January 2002 by U.S. president [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush]] to hold terrorism suspects and "[[illegal enemy combatants]]" during the [[War on terror|Global War on Terrorism]] following the [[September 11 attacks|attacks of September 11, 2001]]. As of January 2025, at least 780 people from 48 countries have been detained at the camp since its creation, of whom 756 had been released or transferred to other detention facilities, 9 [[Death in custody|died in custody]], and 15 remain.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |last=Times |first=The New York |date=2021-05-18 |title=The Guantánamo Docket |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/us/guantanamo-bay-detainees.html |access-date=2024-07-03 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

Shortly after the [[September 11 attacks]], the U.S. declared its "[[war on terror]]" effort and [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|led a multinational military operation]] against [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan (1996–2001)|Taliban-ruled Afghanistan]] to dismantle [[Al-Qaeda]] and capture its leader, [[Osama bin Laden]]. During the invasion, on 13 November 2001, President Bush [[Detention, Treatment, and Trial of Certain Non-Citizens in the War Against Terrorism|issued a military order]] allowing for the [[Indefinite detention without trial|indefinite detention]] of foreign nationals without charge and preventing them from legally challenging their detention. The following month, the [[U.S. Department of Justice]] claimed that ''[[habeas corpus]]''—a [[legal recourse]] against unlawful detention—did not apply to [[Guantanamo military commission|Guantanamo]] Bay because it was outside of U.S. territory. Subsequently, in January 2002, a temporary detention facility dubbed "[[Camp X-Ray]]" was created to house suspected Al-Qaeda members and Taliban fighters primarily [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|captured in Afghanistan]].<ref name="timeline01">{{Cite web |title=Timeline: 20 years of Guantanamo Bay prison |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2022/1/10/timeline-20-years-of-guantanamo-bay-prison |access-date=2024-07-03 |website=Al Jazeera |language=en}}</ref>

By May 2003, the Guantanamo Bay detention camp had grown into a larger and more permanent facility that housed over 680 prisoners, the vast majority without formal charges.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Locked Up Alone: Detention Conditions and Mental Health at Guantanamo: II. The Range of Prison Facilities at Guantanamo |url=https://www.hrw.org/reports/2008/us0608/2.htm |access-date=2024-07-03 |website=www.hrw.org}}</ref><ref name="timeline01"/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Haddad |first=Mohammed |title=Guantanamo Bay explained in maps and charts |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/9/7/guantanamo-bay-explained-in-maps-and-charts-interactive |access-date=2024-07-03 |website=Al Jazeera |language=en}}</ref> The [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] maintained that it was not obliged to grant prisoners basic protections under the [[U.S. Constitution]] or the [[Geneva Conventions]], since the former did not extend to foreign soil and the latter did not apply to "[[Unlawful combatant|unlawful enemy combatants]]". Various humanitarian and legal advocacy groups claimed that these policies were unconstitutional and violated [[international human rights law]];<ref>[http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/issues/security-and-human-rights/guantanamo Guantanamo and Illegal Detention] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015152944/http://www.amnestyusa.org/our-work/issues/security-and-human-rights/guantanamo|date=15 October 2016}}, Amnesty International. Retrieved 3 November 2016</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Guantanamo |url=https://ccrjustice.org/node/4526 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210301034757/https://ccrjustice.org/home/what-we-do/issues/guantanamo |archive-date=1 March 2021 |access-date=2019-05-07 |website=Center for Co

